%description:
MSG_ZEROCOPY completion notification (Workstream H2). Client sends three
separate 500B writes back to back, all marked zerocopy, under Nagle
(default enabled) and no artificial window/cwnd constraint -- so the
first write ships as its own segment immediately (nothing outstanding
yet), while the second and third accumulate in the queue and go out
together in one coalesced segment once the first segment's ACK arrives
(the exact same Nagle-coalescing scenario as tcp_nagle_3.test/
tcp_eor_1.test, this time WITHOUT an eor boundary, so the two do
legitimately coalesce into one segment). This is the case a naive
"one notification per segment" implementation would get wrong: the
second and third writes' completions must BOTH fire off the single
coalesced segment that carries them, with the two writes' own distinct
ids (1 and 2; the first write, unmarked... no -- all three are marked
here, so ids 0, 1, 2, assigned in SEND order) -- not silently merged
into one notification, and not lost.

Falsification: none needed as a separate run -- exactly three distinct
ZEROCOPY_COMPLETION lines (ids 0, 1, 2), with id 0 firing off the first
(solo) segment and ids 1 and 2 both firing off the second (coalesced)
segment, is itself the falsification of "only fires once per segment" or
"ids aren't assigned per-SEND".

%inifile: omnetpp.ini
[General]
record-vector-results = false
ned-path = .;../../../../src;../../lib

network = inet.test.moduletest.lib.TcpTestNet1

cmdenv-event-banners=false
cmdenv-express-mode=false
cmdenv-log-prefix="[%c]: "

*.testing=false

*.tcptester.script=""

*.cli_app.active=true
*.cli_app.localAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.cli_app.localPort=1000
*.cli_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.cli_app.connectPort=2000
*.cli_app.tOpen=0s
*.cli_app.tSend=-1s
*.cli_app.sendBytes=0B
*.cli_app.sendScript="1.0 500 zerocopy; 1.0 500 zerocopy; 1.0 500 zerocopy"
*.cli_app.tClose=-1s

*.srv_app.active=false
*.srv_app.localAddress="10.0.0.2"
*.srv_app.localPort=2000
*.srv_app.connectAddress="10.0.0.1"
*.srv_app.connectPort=1000
*.srv_app.tOpen=0s
*.srv_app.tSend=-1s
*.srv_app.sendBytes=0B
*.srv_app.sendScript=""
*.srv_app.tClose=-1s

*.*_tcp.mss = 1000
*.*_tcp.sackSupport = false
*.*_tcp.windowScalingSupport = false
*.*_tcp.timestampSupport = false
*.*_tcp.tcpAlgorithmClass = "TcpReno"

include ../../lib/tcp-legacy.ini

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# id 0 (first write) ships as its own segment (1:501) immediately -- nothing
%# outstanding yet -- and completes right there.
%contains: stdout
[1.001 A003] A.1000 > B.2000: A 1:501(500) ack 501 win 7504
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
ZEROCOPY_COMPLETION: id=0
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# ids 1 and 2 (second and third writes) coalesce into ONE segment (501:1501)
%# once the first segment's ACK arrives -- both complete off that single segment.
%contains: stdout
[1.005 A004] A.1000 > B.2000: A 501:1501(1000) ack 501 win 7504
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
ZEROCOPY_COMPLETION: id=1
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
ZEROCOPY_COMPLETION: id=2
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
